04058nam a22005055i 9780773562370DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19901990xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735623707 a10.1515/97807735623702doi  a(DE-B1597)655897  a(OCoLC)1316477238  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHD6527bA73 1990eb 7aPOL0400002bisacsh04a322/.2/09711 aArcher, Keith, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPolitical Choices and Electoral Consequences :bA Study of Organized Labour and the New Democratic Party /cKeith Archer. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1990] 4c©1990  a1 online resource (128 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables/Figure -- tAcknowledgments -- tThe Weakness of the NDP in Federal Politics -- tChoosing the Rules of Union-Party Affiliation:A Historical Perspective -- tMeasuring the Union Link to the NDP -- tUnion-Party Affiliation as a Collective Action Problem -- tElectoral Consequences of Union Affiliation -- tExplaining Voting Behaviour in Canada -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe most important link between labour and the NDP is the direct party affiliation of union locals. While this sort of affiliation had existed with the CCF, the Canadian Labour Congress showed a greater commitment to encouraging union locals to affiliate with the NDP. Although, as Archer discusses in both theoretical and empirical terms, individuals who belong to union locals formally linked to the NDP are more likely to vote for that party than are other people with similar socio-demographic characteristics, this has had little positive effect on the NDP's fortunes. Archer reveals that although, in principle, each union local may favour high rates of affiliation, it is often not in a local's self-interest to affiliate. Archer suggests that the main reason for such a disappointing record of affiliation is structural rather than ideological or cultural. He compares the Canadian situation to that in Britain, where the Labour Party rules governing affiliation have supported high rates of affiliation. The rules of the NDP, Archer goes on to show, are not significantly different from those that were developed between labour and the CCF. However, the CCF was not a labour party as such but rather an amalgam of farmers, labourers, and members of constituency associations. Labour's role has consequently remained that of a junior partner with the constituency groups. Under these circumstances, Archer argues, one would expect rates of affiliation to remain low.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356237040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773562370423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773562370/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles